264.text: A fellow who is working at the chemical laboratory up at the hospital

218.text: a short sketch of my adventures

quotes.text: "Whatever have you been doing with yourself, Watson?"
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "You are as thin as a lath and as brown as a nut."
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "Poor devil!"
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "What are you up to now?"
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "Looking for lodgings,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Trying to solve the problem as to whether it is possible to get comfortable rooms at a reasonable price."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "That's a strange thing,"
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "you are the second man to-day that has used that expression to me."
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "And who was the first?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "A fellow who is working at the chemical laboratory up at the hospital. He was bemoaning himself this morning because he could not get someone to go halves with him in some nice rooms which he had found, and which were too much for his purse."
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "By Jove!"
quotes.speaker: he

quotes.text: "if he really wants someone to share the rooms and the expense, I am the very man for him. I should prefer having a partner to being alone."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You don't know Sherlock Holmes yet,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "perhaps you would not care for him as a constant companion."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Why, what is there against him?"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Oh, I didn't say there was anything against him. He is a little queer in his ideas--an enthusiast in some branches of science. As far as I know he is a decent fellow enough."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "A medical student, I suppose?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "No--I have no idea what he intends to go in for. I believe he is well up in anatomy, and he is a first-class chemist; but, as far as I know, he has never taken out any systematic medical classes. His studies are very desultory and eccentric, but he has amassed a lot of out-of-the way knowledge which would astonish his professors."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Did you never ask him what he was going in for?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "No; he is not a man that it is easy to draw out, though he can be communicative enough when the fancy seizes him."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "I should like to meet him,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "If I am to lodge with anyone, I should prefer a man of studious and quiet habits. I am not strong enough yet to stand much noise or excitement. I had enough of both in Afghanistan to last me for the remainder of my natural existence. How could I meet this friend of yours?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "He is sure to be at the laboratory,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "He either avoids the place for weeks, or else he works there from morning to night. If you like, we shall drive round together after luncheon."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Certainly,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You mustn't blame me if you don't get on with him,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I know nothing more of him than I have learned from meeting him occasionally in the laboratory. You proposed this arrangement, so you must not hold me responsible."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "If we don't get on it will be easy to part company,"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "It seems to me, Stamford,"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "that you have some reason for washing your hands of the matter. Is this fellow's temper so formidable, or what is it? Don't be mealy-mouthed about it."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "It is not easy to express the inexpressible,"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Holmes is a little too scientific for my tastes--it approaches to cold-bloodedness. I could imagine his giving a friend a little pinch of the latest vegetable alkaloid, not out of malevolence, you understand, but simply out of a spirit of inquiry in order to have an accurate idea of the effects. To do him justice, I think that he would take it himself with the same readiness. He appears to have a passion for definite and exact knowledge."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Very right too."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Yes, but it may be pushed to excess. When it comes to beating the subjects in the dissecting-rooms with a stick, it is certainly taking rather a bizarre shape."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Beating the subjects!"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Yes, to verify how far bruises may be produced after death. I saw him at it with my own eyes."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "And yet you say he is not a medical student?"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "No. Heaven knows what the objects of his studies are. But here we are, and you must form your own impressions about him."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I've found it! I've found it,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "I have found a re-agent which is precipitated by hoemoglobin, and by nothing else."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Dr. Watson, Mr. Sherlock Holmes,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "How are you?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You have been in Afghanistan, I perceive."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "How on earth did you know that?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Never mind,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "The question now is about hoemoglobin. No doubt you see the significance of this discovery of mine?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "It is interesting, chemically, no doubt,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "but practically--"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Why, man, it is the most practical medico-legal discovery for years. Don't you see that it gives us an infallible test for blood stains. Come over here now!"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Let us have some fresh blood,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Now, I add this small quantity of blood to a litre of water. You perceive that the resulting mixture has the appearance of pure water. The proportion of blood cannot be more than one in a million. I have no doubt, however, that we shall be able to obtain the characteristic reaction."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Ha! ha!"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "What do you think of that?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "It seems to be a very delicate test,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Beautiful! beautiful! The old Guiacum test was very clumsy and uncertain. So is the microscopic examination for blood corpuscles. The latter is valueless if the stains are a few hours old. Now, this appears to act as well whether the blood is old or new. Had this test been invented, there are hundreds of men now walking the earth who would long ago have paid the penalty of their crimes."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Indeed!"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Criminal cases are continually hinging upon that one point. A man is suspected of a crime months perhaps after it has been committed. His linen or clothes are examined, and brownish stains discovered upon them. Are they blood stains, or mud stains, or rust stains, or fruit stains, or what are they? That is a question which has puzzled many an expert, and why? Because there was no reliable test. Now we have the Sherlock Holmes' test, and there will no longer be any difficulty."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You are to be congratulated,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "There was the case of Von Bischoff at Frankfort last year. He would certainly have been hung had this test been in existence. Then there was Mason of Bradford, and the notorious Muller, and Lefevre of Montpellier, and Samson of new Orleans. I could name a score of cases in which it would have been decisive."
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You seem to be a walking calendar of crime,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "You might start a paper on those lines. Call it the 'Police News of the Past.'"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "Very interesting reading it might be made, too,"
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes

quotes.text: "I have to be careful,"
quotes.speaker: Lefevre

quotes.text: "for I dabble with poisons a good deal."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "We came here on business,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "My friend here wants to take diggings, and as you were complaining that you could get no one to go halves with you, I thought that I had better bring you together."
quotes.speaker: Sherlock Holmes

quotes.text: "I have my eye on a suite in Baker Street,"
quotes.speaker: Lefevre

quotes.text: "which would suit us down to the ground. You don't mind the smell of strong tobacco, I hope?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I always smoke 'ship's' myself,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "That's good enough. I generally have chemicals about, and occasionally do experiments. Would that annoy you?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "By no means."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Let me see--what are my other shortcomings. I get in the dumps at times, and don't open my mouth for days on end. You must not think I am sulky when I do that. Just let me alone, and I'll soon be right. What have you to confess now? It's just as well for two fellows to know the worst of one another before they begin to live together."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I keep a bull pup,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "and I object to rows because my nerves are shaken, and I get up at all sorts of ungodly hours, and I am extremely lazy. I have another set of vices when I'm well, but those are the principal ones at present."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Do you include violin-playing in your category of rows?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "It depends on the player,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "A well-played violin is a treat for the gods--a badly-played one--"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Oh, that's all right,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "I think we may consider the thing as settled--that is, if the rooms are agreeable to you."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "When shall we see them?"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Call for me here at noon to-morrow, and we'll go together and settle everything,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "All right--noon exactly,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "By the way,"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "how the deuce did he know that I had come from Afghanistan?"
quotes.speaker: his

quotes.text: "That's just his little peculiarity,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "A good many people have wanted to know how he finds things out."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "Oh! a mystery is it?"
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "This is very piquant. I am much obliged to you for bringing us together. 'The proper study of mankind is man,' you know."
quotes.speaker: him

quotes.text: "You must study him, then,"
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "You'll find him a knotty problem, though. I'll wager he learns more about you than you about him. Good-bye."
quotes.speaker: Unknown

quotes.text: "Good-bye,"
quotes.speaker: him
